Path from Congarees to Fort Moore
properties.description:
The exact route of the historical trail between Savannah Town/Fort Moore and the Congarees is not known, but I have attempted to map its possible route given the available evidence.

The first map to show a trail between Savannah Town/Fort Moore and the Congarees is the 1721 Barnwell map. On this map, the route is pictured as a basically straight line but is shown to cross Town Creek and the South Fork of the Edisto River.

William P. Myers 1923 map of the Trail System of the Southeastern United States in the Early Colonial Period pictures this route as an extension of the Occaneechi Path, which runs between modern Petersburg, Virginia and Augusta, Georgia. Myer gives no written details about the South Carolina portion of this route, but the map shows a distinct bulge near the western end of this segment. This zig-zag in the route clearly follows the rim of the Edisto River watershed, which bypasses the numerous upper tributaries of the Edisto Rivers north and south forks that intersect a more direct course between Savannah Town/Fort Moore and the Congarees.

In reconstructing the possible route, I have for the most part followed existing road beds along this ridge. In keeping with Barnwells map, the route makes two river crossings and avoids others. First, the route crosses Town Creek at a speculative location about six miles east of Fort Moore. Second, the route crosses Shaws Creek, a tributary of the South Fork Edisto River, before turning north and meeting with the main watershed divide. Either Barnwell left the crossing of Shaws Creek off of his map, or, as may be more likely, he considered what we now know as Shaws Creek to be the main headwaters of the South Fork.
